<p>Mr. Israilov testified that he had been beaten 
with gun butts and pistol grips and tortured with 
electric wires and a hot metal rod. In the autumn 
of 2004, Mr. Israilov fled Chechnya and entered 
Austria on 7 September 2005 where he was 
officially granted refugee status after the Federal 
Asylum Senate (Unabh&#228;ngiger Bundesasylsenat) 
found that Mr. Israilov&#8217;s testimony about his 
treatment during his captivity in Chechnya was 
credible.  An expert report dated 14 October 
2005 submitted to the Bundesasylamt by a 
medical doctor confirmed that Mr. Israilov&#8217;s 
scars and injuries fit the descriptions of 
mistreatment in his testimony.  
</p>
<p>After Mr. Israilov left Chechnya, his father, Mr. 
Sharpudi E. Israilov, was also kidnapped on 27 
November 2004 and, according to his testimony, 
detained and tortured by President Kadyrov&#8217;s 
security service for 10 months. This was 
apparently done to try to force his son, Mr. 
Israilov, then living in Vienna, to return to 
Chechnya. Mr. Israilov described in his 
testimony that, starting on 31 May 2008, he had 
been contacted repeatedly personally and by 
phone by a man called Artur Kurmakaev who 
later stated that he was sent by President 
Kadyrov to threaten Israilov&#8217;s family so as to 
force him to return to Chechnya, and to put 
pressure on Mr. Israilov to make him withdraw a 
complaint he had filed with the European Court 
of Human Rights. Mr. Israilov&#8217;s father Sharpudi 
Israilov&#8217;s testimony was also included in the 
complaint as further evidence that President 
Kadyrov had personally tortured detainees and 
was responsible for acts of torture committed by 
</p>
<p>Austrian courts as these were acts committed 
by a foreigner in a country other than Austria 
and because - as Kadyrov failed to enter 
Austria - there was also no connection to 
Austria. 
</p>
<p>As regards Mr. Israilov, his representative 
applied to the Landesamt f&#252;r 
