after consultation with the competent Public 
Prosecutor, no sufficient reasons to grant such 
protection were found. Currently, 
proceedings relating to the killing of Mr. 
Israilov on 13 January 2009 in Vienna are 
being conducted by the Office of the Public 
Prosecution in Vienna. 
</p>
<p>Ramzan Kadyrov is being prosecuted for 
alleged instigation to severe coercion 
according to &#167;&#167; 12, 15, 105 (1), 106 (1) and 
(3) StGB for criminal acts that he allegedly 
committed in Austria. As regards the acts of 
torture that he allegedly committed in 
Chechnya, due to the fact that Ramzan 
Kadyrov did not travel to Austria, no link for 
Austrian jurisdiction according to the relevant 
provisions of the Austrian penal code. 
</p>
<p>As regards Mr. Israilov, the Austrian Code of 
Police Practice (Sicherheitspolizeigesetz; 
SPG) does not provide a legal entitlement for 
police protection upon the request of an 
individual.  Decisive for the question whether 
police protection can be granted is the 
presumption that a dangerous attack is 
imminent. Mr. Israilov had been questioned 
in writing and, despite the questioning of 
additional witnesses and information received </p>

