<p>Addis Ababa, in a cell measuring 2 m2 which is 
reported to be often unbearably hot. It is 
believed that her arrest might have been carried 
out in connection with a trip to Europe in 
November 2008 during which she discussed the 
terms of her previous release from prison. 
Ethiopian government media reported that she 
had denied apologizing for the crimes she had 
allegedly committed and that she was given 
three days to revoke her statement. Shortly 
afterwards, the Pardons Board decided to recant 
her pardon and to re-impose her original life 
sentence passed in 2007.  
</p>
<p>Ms. Mideksa, together with thousands of 
individuals including opposition 
parliamentarians, opposition party leaders, 
journalists and human rights defenders, had been 
arrested in 2005 following demonstrations 
against the results of elections held in May 
</p><p>2005. In 2006, Ms. Mideksa was charged with 
treason, tried and sentenced to life 
imprisonment. The majority of those found 
guilty were released in 2007 following pardons 
after they had negotiated an agreement with the 
Government and signed letters of apology. 
However the exact terms and conditions of 
pardon remain unclear. Since her arrest Ms. 
Mideksa has reportedly been allowed one visit 
from her close family but has not been granted 
access to legal counsel or medical treatment. She 
has refused food to protest against her arrest and 
detention.  
</p>
<p>During her arrest a person who was with her, 
Professor Mesfin Weldemariam, was severely 
beaten by one security officer with a rifle butt. 
He sustained injuries to his leg as a result of the 
</p>
<p>Government was carried out in accordance 
with the law in force on the subject. She was 
arrested and detained also in accordance with 
the law, with due regard to her rights under 
the Constitution and international human 
rights instruments. Her case was tried in fair 
proceedings before an independent and 
impartial court. She was convicted of crimes 
against the constitutional order and sentenced 
to life imprisonment. She was not subjected 
to special treatment, nor was she denied her 
right to be visited by her family. Federal 
Prison Administration reported that since her 
detention, she has maintained contact with 
her family, in particular with her mother, 
daughter and sister on Saturdays and 
Sundays. The Government is unaware of Ms. 
Mideksa&#8217;s refusal of food to protect against 
her detention. In contrast, her family is 
providing her with daily meals. Ms. Mideksa 
is also in contact with her lawyer. She is 
being treated as any other person under the 
protection of the law, with due regard to her 
physical and mental integrity.  
</p>
<p>Ms. Mideksa and others in the leadership of 
the former Coalition for Unity and 
Democracy (CUD) party were granted 
conditional pardon by the President on 19 
July 2007, after submitting a signed written 
petition. Ms. Mideksa misrepresented the 
circumstances of the pardon on several 
occasions, by making an open statement to 
her supporters saying &#8220;she did not make any 
plea for pardon&#8221;, and rather that the pardon 
had been granted solely through the 
intervention of elders and by pressure from 
her supporters. Ms. Mideksa denied her 
request for pardon to the Ethiopian </p>

